narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned about statics and a bit of methods of materials.
Understanding of static mechanics, strength and deformation of materials. Introduction to design considerations of material, shape, and joints.
Basic understanding of the behavior of materials and the distribution of forces on structures in equilibrium.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Doc A was super engaging which makes a huge difference in getting through those 3-hour long summer classes. I also liked the organization. The homework matched what we were learning and the quizzes felt manageable.

A strength of this course is the broadness of the material covered, while still maintaining an in depth introduction to the math behind static mechanics. A weakness would be that the class is very high pace, but that is to be expected for a summer class.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes. I would highly recommend taking this class with Doc A if you have the opportunity or are considering a summer class.
Definitely if you are pursuing mechanical engineering (you have to), or even if you just want a more real world application of some basic physics. Having an understanding of how things stay upright.

Yes I would recommend this course to another student. It provided a ton of essential information and was a great introduction to real life applications of physics problems and mechanical engineering problems.

narratives.question_text: The Canvas course site allowed me to identify and access required course materials easily.
How will you use the knowledge and skills you learned in this course in your future endeavors?
comments: I really enjoy working with my hands and tinkering, building, and just exploring electrical and mechanical mechanisms. I will use the concepts I learned in this course during my capstone project for structural considerations, as well as in my job for having an insight into what will be sturdily constructed even without running the numbers.
I hope to apply what i've learned in this class to future classes and internships/job opportunities.
